</taxonomicNameLabel>
may be distinguished from other species of 
<taxonomicName id="4C724D18FF8CD521CABEF959D724F951" box="[1180,1294,1755,1780]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Hypotelus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="26" pageNumber="477" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B906EA89FF8CD521CABEF959D724F951" box="[1180,1294,1755,1780]" italics="true" pageId="26" pageNumber="477">Hypotelus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the color pattern of the elytra (
<figureCitation id="13492A1EFF8CD521CFA1F97CD3FEF8B2" box="[387,468,1790,1815]" captionStart="FIGURES 9 – 19" captionStartId="9.[151,264,1913,1935]" captionTargetBox="[216,1355,230,1832]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[151,1436,157,1945]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 9 – 19. Habitus, dorsal view. 9, Hypotelus insulanus, syntype, male; 10, H. praecox, lectotype, female; 11, H. scheerpeltzi sp. nov., holotype, male; 12, H. testaceus, syntype, male; 13, H. melanodelta sp. nov., holotype, female; 14, H. castaneus sp. nov., holotype, male; 15, H. brevitarsus sp. nov., holotype, male; 16, H. corniculatus sp. nov., holotype, female; 17, H. marginatus, syntype, male; 18, H. laevis, male; 19, H. andinus. Scale bars = 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/803652/files/figure.png" pageId="26" pageNumber="477">Fig. 11</figureCitation>
); males are distinguished by median lobe of aedeagus thinner in lateral view and apex as a hook (
<figureCitation id="13492A1EFF8CD521CF32F8A3D349F89F" box="[272,355,1825,1850]" captionStart="FIGURES 59 – 74" captionStartId="17.[151,264,1924,1946]" captionTargetBox="[290,1268,229,1830]" captionTargetId="figure@17.[237,1336,193,1893]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="FIGURES 59 – 74. Aedeagus, for each species with lateral view and ventral view, respectively. 59 – 60, Hypotelus pusillus; 61 – 62, H. insulanus; 63 – 64, H. marginatus; 65 – 66, H. testaceus; 67 – 68, H. praecox; 69 – 70, H. brevitarsus sp. nov., parameres removed in ventral view; 71 – 72, H. castaneus sp. nov.; 73 – 74, H. scheerpeltzi sp. nov. Scale bars = 0.125 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/803662/files/figure.png" pageId="26" pageNumber="477">Fig. 73</figureCitation>
); females are distinguished by the shape of tergite 10 and bursa copulatrix (
<figureCitation id="13492A1EFF8CD521CA90F8A3D772F89F" box="[1202,1368,1825,1850]" captionStart="FIGURES 83 – 108" captionStartId="19.[151,264,1784,1806]" captionTargetBox="[245,1323,259,1717]" captionTargetId="figure@19.[207,1375,193,1777]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="FIGURES 83 – 108. Tergites in dorsal view, right setae removed, and genitalia of female. 83 – 84, Hypotelus pusillus. 83, tergite 9, 10 and bursa copulatrix; 84, spermatheca. 85 – 86, H. insulanus. 85, tergite 10; 86, spermatheca. 87, H. marginatus, spermatheca. 88 – 90, H. testaceus. 88, bursa copulatrix; 89, tergite 10; 90, spermatheca. 91, H. melanodelta sp. nov., spermatheca. 92 – 94, H. praecox. 92, bursa copulatrix; 93, tergite 10; 94, spermatheca, 95 – 97, H. castaneus sp. nov. 95, bursa copulatrix; 96, tergite 10; 97, spermatheca. 98 – 99, H. brevitarsus sp. nov. 98, tergite 10; 99, spermatheca. 100 – 102, H. corniculatus sp. nov. 100, bursa copulatrix; 101, tergite 10; 102, spermatheca. 103 – 105, H. laevis. 103, bursa copulatrix; 104, tergite 10; 105, spermatheca. 106 – 108, H. scheerpeltzi sp. nov. 106, bursa copulatrix; 107, tergite 10; 108, spermatheca. Scale bars = 0.125 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/803666/files/figure.png" pageId="26" pageNumber="477">Figs. 106–108</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C3686510FF8CD520CEE5F8C7D3DAFCB0" lastPageId="27" lastPageNumber="478" pageId="26" pageNumber="477" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BCD369BFF8CD521CEE5F8C7D141F84C" blockId="26.[151,1437,1368,2026]" pageId="26" pageNumber="477">
<emphasis id="B906EA89FF8CD521CEE5F8C7D373F8FB" bold="true" box="[199,345,1861,1886]" pageId="26" pageNumber="477">Description.</emphasis>
BL: 3.0– 
<quantity id="4C8A9B7EFF8CD521CFE7F8C7D036F8F8" box="[453,540,1861,1885]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.3" pageId="26" pageNumber="477" unit="mm" value="3.3">3.3 mm</quantity>
, BW: 
<quantity id="4C8A9B7EFF8CD521CC46F8C7D097F8F8" box="[612,701,1861,1885]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.0" pageId="26" pageNumber="477" unit="mm" value="0.8">0.8 mm</quantity>
. Body slightly convex; dorsal surface glossy; dark brown, except elytra yellowish (with two transverse darker areas, basal and apical) (
<figureCitation id="13492A1EFF8CD521CDCFF8EAD66CF825" box="[1005,1094,1896,1921]" captionStart="FIGURES 9 – 19" captionStartId="9.[151,264,1913,1935]" captionTargetBox="[216,1355,230,1832]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[151,1436,157,1945]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 9 – 19. Habitus, dorsal view. 9, Hypotelus insulanus, syntype, male; 10, H. praecox, lectotype, female; 11, H. scheerpeltzi sp. nov., holotype, male; 12, H. testaceus, syntype, male; 13, H. melanodelta sp. nov., holotype, female; 14, H. castaneus sp. nov., holotype, male; 15, H. brevitarsus sp. nov., holotype, male; 16, H. corniculatus sp. nov., holotype, female; 17, H. marginatus, syntype, male; 18, H. laevis, male; 19, H. andinus. Scale bars = 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/803652/files/figure.png" pageId="26" pageNumber="477">Fig. 11</figureCitation>
); appendages lighter, except mandibles and antennomeres 4–11. Dorsal integument of head and pronotum with dispersed fine punctures and undulate microstriae absent on basal disc of head and on disc of pronotum; elytra with dispersed fine punctures and only one longitudinal finely punctate stria close to elytral suture.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BCD369BFF8DD520CEE5FF15D303FF5D" blockId="27.[151,1437,151,968]" pageId="27" pageNumber="478">
<emphasis id="B906EA89FF8DD520CEE5FF15D366FF15" box="[199,332,151,176]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="478">Male. Head</emphasis>
. Supra-antennal area slightly prominent. Antennae inserted ventrally and passing humeral angle; antennomeres 2 and 3 of equal length; 5–11 gradually increasing in length toward antennal apex. Mandibles symmetrical.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BCD369BFF8DD520CEE5FE86D0D3FE2D" blockId="27.[151,1437,151,968]" pageId="27" pageNumber="478">
<emphasis id="B906EA89FF8DD520CEE5FE86D332FEB8" box="[199,280,260,285]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="478">Thorax</emphasis>
. Pronotum wider than long (PW/PL=1.5); anterior angles rounded and slightly prominent; apical half with somewhat parallel sides and basal half gradually narrowing toward the base; with complete internal midlongitudinal ridge and slight longitudinal median sulcus only on basal two-third. Elytra somewhat longer than wide (EL/BW=1.2), can partially cover abdominal tergite 3.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BCD369BFF8DD520CEE5FE16D156FD99" blockId="27.[151,1437,151,968]" pageId="27" pageNumber="478">
<emphasis id="B906EA89FF8DD520CEE5FE16D31BFE08" box="[199,305,404,429]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="478">Abdomen</emphasis>
. Tergite 8 with posterior margin truncate (
<figureCitation id="13492A1EFF8DD520CD28FE16D174FE09" box="[778,862,404,429]" captionStart="FIGURES 48 – 58" captionStartId="16.[151,264,1844,1866]" captionTargetBox="[200,1385,250,1781]" captionTargetId="figure@16.[151,1436,193,1823]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIGURES 48 – 58. Tergites and sternites of males in dorsal and ventral view, respectively and right setae removed. 48, Hypotelus pusillus, tergite 8; 49, H. scheerpeltzi sp. nov., tergite 8; 50, H. castaneus sp. nov., tergite 8; 51, H. pusillus, sternite 8; 52, H. insulanus, sternite 8; 53, H. testaceus, sternite 8; 54, H. castaneus sp. nov., sternite 8; 55, H. pusillus, tergites 9 and 10; 56, H. insulanus, tergite 10; 57, H. castaneus sp. nov., tergite 10; 58, H. brevitarsus sp. nov., tergite 10. Scale bars = 0.125 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/803660/files/figure.png" pageId="27" pageNumber="478">Fig. 49</figureCitation>
); sternite 8 at posterior margin with a small weakly pigmented strip and short setae; tergite 9 with short ventral struts; sternite 9 with posterior margin truncate and with two pairs of long setae; tergite 10 with posterior margin weakly pigmented, short fringes and four setae on each side. Median lobe of aedeagus with slightly bulbous base and apex somewhat pointed in ventral view; curved shape and thin in lateral view, with apex curved as a hook (
<figureCitation id="13492A1EFF8DD520CCC4FDA6D15AFD99" box="[742,880,548,573]" captionStart="FIGURES 59 – 74" captionStartId="17.[151,264,1924,1946]" captionTargetBox="[290,1268,229,1830]" captionTargetId="figure@17.[237,1336,193,1893]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="FIGURES 59 – 74. Aedeagus, for each species with lateral view and ventral view, respectively. 59 – 60, Hypotelus pusillus; 61 – 62, H. insulanus; 63 – 64, H. marginatus; 65 – 66, H. testaceus; 67 – 68, H. praecox; 69 – 70, H. brevitarsus sp. nov., parameres removed in ventral view; 71 – 72, H. castaneus sp. nov.; 73 – 74, H. scheerpeltzi sp. nov. Scale bars = 0.125 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/803662/files/figure.png" pageId="27" pageNumber="478">Figs. 73–74</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BCD369BFF8DD520CEE5FDC5D330FD69" blockId="27.[151,1437,151,968]" pageId="27" pageNumber="478">
<emphasis id="B906EA89FF8DD520CEE5FDC5D331FDC5" box="[199,283,583,608]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="478">Female</emphasis>
. Similar to male except for: abdominal sternite 8 with posterior margin sinuous (
<figureCitation id="13492A1EFF8DD520CAE0FDC5D733FDC5" box="[1218,1305,583,608]" captionStart="FIGURES 75 – 82" captionStartId="18.[151,264,1403,1425]" captionTargetBox="[194,1368,254,1322]" captionTargetId="figure@18.[151,1436,193,1381]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="FIGURES 75 – 82. Sternite 8 of females in ventral view, right setae removed. 75, Hypotelus pusillus; 76, H. insulanus; 77, H. marginatus; 78 H. testaceus; 79, H. melanodelta sp. nov.; 80, H. brevitarsus sp. nov.; 81, H. castaneus sp. nov.; 82, H. scheerpeltzi sp. nov. Scale bars = 0.125 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/803664/files/figure.png" pageId="27" pageNumber="478">Fig. 82</figureCitation>
); tergite 10 truncate at apex (
<figureCitation id="13492A1EFF8DD520CF74FDEED392FD21" box="[342,440,620,645]" captionStart="FIGURES 83 – 108" captionStartId="19.[151,264,1784,1806]" captionTargetBox="[245,1323,259,1717]" captionTargetId="figure@19.[207,1375,193,1777]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="FIGURES 83 – 108. Tergites in dorsal view, right setae removed, and genitalia of female. 83 – 84, Hypotelus pusillus. 83, tergite 9, 10 and bursa copulatrix; 84, spermatheca. 85 – 86, H. insulanus. 85, tergite 10; 86, spermatheca. 87, H. marginatus, spermatheca. 88 – 90, H. testaceus. 88, bursa copulatrix; 89, tergite 10; 90, spermatheca. 91, H. melanodelta sp. nov., spermatheca. 92 – 94, H. praecox. 92, bursa copulatrix; 93, tergite 10; 94, spermatheca, 95 – 97, H. castaneus sp. nov. 95, bursa copulatrix; 96, tergite 10; 97, spermatheca. 98 – 99, H. brevitarsus sp. nov. 98, tergite 10; 99, spermatheca. 100 – 102, H. corniculatus sp. nov. 100, bursa copulatrix; 101, tergite 10; 102, spermatheca. 103 – 105, H. laevis. 103, bursa copulatrix; 104, tergite 10; 105, spermatheca. 106 – 108, H. scheerpeltzi sp. nov. 106, bursa copulatrix; 107, tergite 10; 108, spermatheca. Scale bars = 0.125 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/803666/files/figure.png" pageId="27" pageNumber="478">Fig. 107</figureCitation>
); bursa copulatrix forming like a narrow ring (
<figureCitation id="13492A1EFF8DD520CD9EFDEED634FD20" box="[956,1054,620,645]" captionStart="FIGURES 83 – 108" captionStartId="19.[151,264,1784,1806]" captionTargetBox="[245,1323,259,1717]" captionTargetId="figure@19.[207,1375,193,1777]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="FIGURES 83 – 108. Tergites in dorsal view, right setae removed, and genitalia of female. 83 – 84, Hypotelus pusillus. 83, tergite 9, 10 and bursa copulatrix; 84, spermatheca. 85 – 86, H. insulanus. 85, tergite 10; 86, spermatheca. 87, H. marginatus, spermatheca. 88 – 90, H. testaceus. 88, bursa copulatrix; 89, tergite 10; 90, spermatheca. 91, H. melanodelta sp. nov., spermatheca. 92 – 94, H. praecox. 92, bursa copulatrix; 93, tergite 10; 94, spermatheca, 95 – 97, H. castaneus sp. nov. 95, bursa copulatrix; 96, tergite 10; 97, spermatheca. 98 – 99, H. brevitarsus sp. nov. 98, tergite 10; 99, spermatheca. 100 – 102, H. corniculatus sp. nov. 100, bursa copulatrix; 101, tergite 10; 102, spermatheca. 103 – 105, H. laevis. 103, bursa copulatrix; 104, tergite 10; 105, spermatheca. 106 – 108, H. scheerpeltzi sp. nov. 106, bursa copulatrix; 107, tergite 10; 108, spermatheca. Scale bars = 0.125 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/803666/files/figure.png" pageId="27" pageNumber="478">Fig. 106</figureCitation>
); ovipositor consisting of a pair of weakly pigmented hemisternites and a pair of more apical coxites, and with many long setae on apex; spermatheca as 
<figureCitation id="13492A1EFF8DD520CE97FD36D33CFD69" box="[181,278,692,717]" captionStart="FIGURES 83 – 108" captionStartId="19.[151,264,1784,1806]" captionTargetBox="[245,1323,259,1717]" captionTargetId="figure@19.[207,1375,193,1777]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="FIGURES 83 – 108. Tergites in dorsal view, right setae removed, and genitalia of female. 83 – 84, Hypotelus pusillus. 83, tergite 9, 10 and bursa copulatrix; 84, spermatheca. 85 – 86, H. insulanus. 85, tergite 10; 86, spermatheca. 87, H. marginatus, spermatheca. 88 – 90, H. testaceus. 88, bursa copulatrix; 89, tergite 10; 90, spermatheca. 91, H. melanodelta sp. nov., spermatheca. 92 – 94, H. praecox. 92, bursa copulatrix; 93, tergite 10; 94, spermatheca, 95 – 97, H. castaneus sp. nov. 95, bursa copulatrix; 96, tergite 10; 97, spermatheca. 98 – 99, H. brevitarsus sp. nov. 98, tergite 10; 99, spermatheca. 100 – 102, H. corniculatus sp. nov. 100, bursa copulatrix; 101, tergite 10; 102, spermatheca. 103 – 105, H. laevis. 103, bursa copulatrix; 104, tergite 10; 105, spermatheca. 106 – 108, H. scheerpeltzi sp. nov. 106, bursa copulatrix; 107, tergite 10; 108, spermatheca. Scale bars = 0.125 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/803666/files/figure.png" pageId="27" pageNumber="478">Fig. 108</figureCitation>
.
</paragraph>
